Tools/equipment you should practice before taking the test

Before taking the Computer Systems Servicing NC II (CSS NC II) assessment from the Technical Education and Skills Development Authority (TESDA), 
it’s important to practice using the common tools and equipment that computer technicians use. These are usually the same tools available during the assessment. 💻🔧

  
🔧 Hand Tools

These are the basic tools you should be comfortable using:

Phillips screwdriver – for opening and assembling computer cases

Flat-head screwdriver – sometimes used for certain screws or connectors

Long-nose pliers – for holding or bending small parts

Side cutter – for cutting wires or cable ties

Tweezers – for handling small components




💡 Practice removing and reinstalling components like RAM, HDD/SSD, and power connectors.




🌐 Networking Tools

These are very important because networking is a big part of the exam.

Crimping tool – used to attach RJ45 connectors to Ethernet cables

LAN cable tester – checks if the cable wiring is correct

Wire stripper – removes cable insulation

Punch-down tool – used for patch panels or keystone jacks

You should practice making:

Straight-through cable

Crossover cable

Using T568A and T568B wiring standards





🧰 Computer Hardware Components

You should be able to identify and install these:

Motherboard

Processor (CPU)

RAM

Power Supply Unit (PSU)

Hard Disk Drive (HDD) / Solid State Drive (SSD)

Graphics card (if available)

Practice:
-Installing RAM
-Connecting SATA and power cables
-Installing storage drives





🛡️ ESD and Safety Equipment

TESDA assessors also check if you follow proper safety procedures.
-Anti-static wrist strap
-Anti-static mat
-Cleaning brush or blower
-Cable ties





💻 Software / Digital Tools

You should know basic use of:
-Operating system installer (USB boot)
-BIOS/UEFI settings
-Disk partitioning during OS installation
-Basic network commands like:  ipconfig, ping



📡 Networking Devices
-Practice connecting and configuring:
-Router
-Switch
-Wireless access point
-Ethernet cables

You may be asked to:
-Assign IP addresses
-Test connectivity between computers.

  
✅ Quick Tip:
Most candidates fail because they don’t practice LAN cable crimping enough. Make sure you can finish and test a cable correctly in a few minutes.




