A typical CSS NC II practical exam scenario so you can practice like the real test.

Practical exam scenario similar to what candidates experience in the Computer Systems Servicing NC II (CSS NC II) assessment
from the Technical Education and Skills Development Authority (TESDA). The tasks simulate a real technician job order. 💻🔧

Sample CSS NC II Practical Exam Scenario:

You are hired as a computer technician in a small office. The office needs a new computer system assembled and connected to a network 
so employees can share files and access the internet.

Your task is to assemble, configure, and test the system according to the requirements.

Task 1 – Prepare the Work Area

Before starting:
-Wear anti-static wrist strap
-Prepare tools (screwdriver, crimping tool, LAN tester)
-Check all computer components
-Follow ESD safety procedures

The assessor checks if you follow proper safety and workplace procedures.




Task 2 – Assemble the Computer

You will be given computer parts such as:
-Motherboard
-CPU with heatsink
-RAM
-HDD/SSD
-Power Supply Unit (PSU)
-Computer case

You must:
-Install the CPU and heatsink
-Install RAM
-Mount the motherboard in the case
-Install storage drive
-Connect SATA and power cables
-Connect front panel connectors

✔ The system must power on successfully.

Task 3 – Install Operating System

You must install the operating system using a bootable USB.

Steps usually expected:

Enter BIOS/UEFI setup

Set USB as first boot device

Install the OS

Create a user account

Install device drivers

Install basic software

After installation:

Check Device Manager

Confirm no missing drivers.

Task 4 – Create a Network Cable

You will create a straight-through LAN cable.

Requirements:

Use UTP cable

Follow T568B color standard

Attach RJ45 connectors

Use crimping tool

Test cable using LAN tester

Color order for T568B:

White-Orange

Orange

White-Green

Blue

White-Blue

Green

White-Brown

Brown

✔ The LAN tester must show 1–8 correct connection.

Task 5 – Set Up Network Connection

You must connect the computer to a small network.

Example configuration:

IP Address:

192.168.1.10


Subnet Mask:

255.255.255.0


Default Gateway:

192.168.1.1


Then test connectivity using command prompt:

ping 192.168.1.1


If replies are received, the network is working.

Task 6 – Printer or File Sharing Setup

You may also be asked to:

Enable file sharing

Share a folder on the network

Connect to a shared printer

Task 7 – Troubleshooting

The assessor may simulate a problem such as:

Network cable not working

Missing driver

Incorrect IP configuration

You must:

Identify the problem

Fix it

Explain what you did

Task 8 – Documentation

Finally, you may be required to fill out a job order or service report including:

Work performed

Problems found

Solutions applied

Tools used

✅ Typical Assessment Time

4 to 8 hours total depending on the training center.

⭐ Pro Tip:
Many assessors fail candidates because they forget small details, like:

Not testing the LAN cable

Not installing drivers

Incorrect IP address format
